1st ggplot2 Graph (Bar Chart)

Brief Dataset Explanation:

1st Graph uses data from a 2015-2023 dataset provided by the Korean Statistical Information Service (KOSIS), a government-run website that reports fertility rates for each province.

# First ggplot2 Graph (Bar Chart)

# We used abbreviation of provinces' names, instead of full name. The reason is 
#that the province's names are long.(We added the abbreviation list below the 
#1st Graph output)

# Importing Korean Birth Rate (By Province) Dataset

birthrate <-
  read_xlsx("data/birthrate.xlsx") 

birthrate <- birthrate |>
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("20"),
    names_to = "year",
    values_to = "birthrate"
  )

# Making a Bar Chart

ggplot(
  birthrate, 
  mapping = aes(x = Province, y = birthrate, fill = year, alpha = birthrate)) +
  facet_wrap(~ year) +
  coord_flip() + 
  geom_col(width = 0.5) +
  scale_alpha_continuous(range = c(0.4, 1)) +  
  labs(title = "Annual Birth Rate by Province in South Korea (2015 - 2023)",
       subtitle = "Urbanized areas show lower fertility rates; however,\nSejong (SJG), a newly established city,\nexhibits an exceptionally high rate.", 
       x = "Province",
       y = "Birthrate (%)",
       caption = 
         "Data Source: Korean Statistical Information Service (KOSIS)") +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 15),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 8, color = "Dark Blue"),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 13),
    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 5),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 4))

Abbreviations for Each Provinces:

  7. Daejeon â DJN

  9. Sejong-si â SJG
  10. Gyeonggi-do â GGD
  11. Gangwon-do â GWD

2nd ggplot2 Graph (Scatterplot)

Brief Dataset Explanation:

The data used in Graph 2 come from datasets spanning 2015 to 2023 that reflect provincial fertility rates and housing prices, sourced from KOSIS.

# Second ggplot2 Graph (Scatterplot)

# Importing Korean Housing Price (By Province) Dataset

housingprice <-
  read_xlsx("data/housingprice.xlsx") 

housingprice <- housingprice |>
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("20"),
    names_to = "year",
    values_to = "housingprice"
  )

housingprice <- housingprice |>
  mutate(housingprice = as.numeric(housingprice))

# We merged two different datasets into one dataset

scatterplotdata <- full_join(birthrate, housingprice)

scatterplotdata <- scatterplotdata |>
  filter(Province %in% c("SEO"))

# Making a Scatterplot

ggplot(scatterplotdata, aes(x = housingprice, y = birthrate)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, color = "red") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "orange") +
  labs(
    title = "Housing Prices vs. Birth Rates in Seoul (2015 - 2023)",
    subtitle = "A closer look at Seoulâdespite having the lowest fertility rateâ\nreveals that higher housing prices correspond with lower birth rates.", 
    y = "Birthrate (%)", 
    caption = "Data Source: Korean Statistical Information Service (KOSIS)") + 
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 15),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 8, color = "Dark Blue"),
    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 5),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 4))

Indicator Definition and Interpretation:

KOSIS mentions that indicators ârefers to a value calculated by using the price ratio between the base period and the survey period conducted every period, converted into a figure where the base period is set to 100.â

3rd ggplot2 Graph (Histogram)

Brief Dataset Explanation:

The data used in Graph 3 come from datasets spanning 2015 to 2023 that capture monthly working hours across various age groups, sourced from KOSIS

# Third ggplot2 Graph (Histogram)

# Importing Korean Working Hours Dataset (By Age Group)

workhour <- read_xlsx("data/workhour.xlsx")

workhour <- workhour |>
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("20"),
    names_to = "year",
    values_to = "workhour"
  )

# Making a Histogram

ggplot(workhour, 
       mapping = aes(x = workhour, fill = Agegroup, colour = Agegroup)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Monthly Working Hours by Age Groups (2015 - 2023)",
       subtitle = "In 2023, the average working hours was 157.6 hours.\nThe analysis reveals that the '30-49' age group has the longest working hours, which are above the average level.",
       x = "Monthly Working Hours",
       y = "Frequency of Age Group",
       caption = "Data Source: Korean Statistical Information Service (KOSIS)") +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 15),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 8, color = "Dark Blue"),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 13),
    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 5),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 4))

4th ggplot2 Graph (Line Plot)

Breif Dataset Explanation:

The data used in 4th Graph come from a dataset spanning 2016 to 2023 that reflects Seoulâs annual household expenditures on private education, sourced from KOSIS.

# Fourth ggplot2 Graph (Lineplot)

# Importing Seoul's Annual Household Expenditures on Private Education Dataset

seoul_edu <- 
  read_excel("data/seoul_edu.xlsx")

# Due to missing data in year 2015, we use data from 2016 to 2023 in this part.

# Making a Lineplot

ggplot(seoul_edu, aes(x = Year, y = Expenditures)) +
  geom_line(color = "red", size = 1) +
  geom_point(color = "orange", size = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2016:2023) +
  labs(
    title = "Private Education Expenditures in Seoul (2016-2023)",
    subtitle = "From 2016 to 2019, annual household expenditures on private education\n
in Seoul increased steadily. In 2020, there was a slight dip, which may\n
have been influenced by the COVID-19 pandemic. However, from 2020\n
through 2023, expenditures increased sharply.",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Private Education Expenditure (billion Won)",
    caption = "Data Source: Korean Statistical Information Service (KOSIS)"
  ) +
   theme_minimal()

1st Graph Output Explanation:

Even in South Korea, where low birth rates are a serious concern, regional disparities in fertility rates are widening, primarily due to differences in infrastructure. Sejongâthe region with the highest birth rate in our graphâwas established in 2012 when the central government relocated there. The cityâs advanced infrastructure and concentration of residents with stable employment may be key factors driving its high birth rate. While birth rates are influenced by a variety of factors such as jobs, housing, and education, Sejong seems to effectively integrate all three. In contrast, although Seoul offers abundant employment opportunities, its high housing prices contribute to its lower birth rate.

2nd Graph Output Explanation:

From the scatter plot, we observe a strong negative correlation between housing prices and birth rate in Seoul. The fitted regression line slopes downward, indicating that higher housing prices are associated with lower birth rates. One possible interpretation is that as housing costs increase, financial constraints or concerns about affordability may lead some families to delay or reduce childbearing. However, it is important to note that correlation does not imply causation. Other factors could also influence birth rates.

3rd Graph Output Explanation:

The histogram displays the distribution of monthly working hours for different age groups from 2015-2023. KOSIS data reveals that the overall average working hours for 2023 is 157.6 hours. The histogram reveals that individuals aged 30 to 49 work significantly longer than the average level. This extended work duration indicates that middle-aged individuals are dedicating more time to their careers compared to other age groups. Such prolonged working hours may contribute to delayed family planning, which in turn could be a factor in Seoulâs low fertility rate.

4th Graph Output Explanation:

Because of the missing data in 2015, we use Seoulâs Annual Household Expenditures on Private Education from 2016 to 2023. The fourth Graph shows a generally upward trend in these expenditures over this period. Despite some fluctuations in 2020âlikely influenced by the COVID-19 outbreak. By 2023, expenditures are noticeably higher than in 2016, which suggest that households are investing more in private education over time. Importantly, this rising trend may help explain Seoulâs low fertility rate, as higher private education costs can place additional financial burdens on families, potentially discouraging them from having more children. Thus, private education expenditures can be an important factor influencing Seoulâs birth rate.

Conclusion

In summary, our analysis demonstrates that Seoulâs low fertility rate is shaped by a complex interplay of socio-economic factors related to housing, employment, and education. The visualizations reveal that while regions like Sejong benefit from integrated infrastructure and stable employment, Seoulâs high housing prices are closely linked to reduced fertility rates. The negative correlation between housing prices and birth rates, combined with the extended working hours observed in the 30-49 age group and the steadily rising private education expenditures, underscores the multifaceted pressures faced by Seoulâs families. These findings suggest that single-factor interventions, such as baby bonuses, are unlikely to be sufficient; instead, comprehensive cross-sector reforms are needed. Potential policy measures include stabilizing housing markets through increased supply and price controls, implementing progressive labor policies (e.g., mandatory parental leave and flexible working hours), and enhancing public education to reduce the reliance on expensive private tutoring, with additional crisis-responsive social safety nets to mitigate economic shocks.
